  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Bunyeong Ferry
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the sound of flowing water, evening turns to dawn again.
    The coastal village lies desolate, its fences worn thin.
    In the heart of the lake, the moon stamps its seal,
    while the ferry mouth greedily swallows the incoming tide.
    Waves pound the ancient stone until it becomes a whetstone;
    the broken ship, moss-buried, lies as a bridge.
    How can my brush capture all the ten thousand scenes of this landscape?
    I wish I could borrow a painter's hand to render it in vermillion and jade.
  footnotes:
    - Bunyeong (扶寧) refers to a coastal region in medieval Korea, known for its strategic port location.
    - The moon 'stamping its seal' (도장 찍었는데) is a metaphor for the moon's reflection appearing perfectly centered in the still lake water.
    - The broken ship becoming a bridge represents the passage of time and nature's transformation of human artifacts.
    - The final couplet expresses the poet's humility before nature's grandeur—only visual art could adequately capture such scenery.
